1
00:01:22,667 --> 00:01:23,748
Town hall, please.

2
00:01:23,875 --> 00:01:25,411
Very good, sir.

3
00:02:37,750 --> 00:02:39,662
It's valuation,
but it's kind of complicated

4
00:02:39,792 --> 00:02:41,872
because part of the property
is outside the boundary.

5
00:02:41,958 --> 00:02:43,165
Is it type one or type two?

6
00:02:43,292 --> 00:02:45,409
- Oh, Mr Barnes.
- I thought it would be Mr Barnes.

7
00:02:45,542 --> 00:02:48,455
- Yes, love?
- My name is Lampton, Joe Lampton.

8
00:02:48,583 --> 00:02:51,542
Oh, yes, you're coming to work here,
aren't you?

9
00:02:52,625 --> 00:02:54,082
One moment, please.

10
00:03:04,750 --> 00:03:06,867
I'm sorry, sir,
what were you saying?

11
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:08,741
Mr Hoylake will see you right away.

12
00:03:08,875 --> 00:03:10,787
My name's Young.
Thanks very much.

13
00:03:14,208 --> 00:03:17,997
Come in.
We didn't expect you until Monday.

14
00:03:19,958 --> 00:03:20,958
Sit down.

15
00:03:25,875 --> 00:03:27,992
We're not accustomed
to such an excess of zeal.

16
00:03:28,125 --> 00:03:30,242
Well, it's not exactly that,
Mr Hoylake. I...

17
00:03:30,375 --> 00:03:33,539
I'm not surprised that you wanted
to leave Dufdon as soon as possible.

18
00:03:34,042 --> 00:03:37,410
You'll find big differences here,
you know? Not only the work.

19
00:03:37,542 --> 00:03:39,374
You'll meet a different class of people.

20
00:03:40,292 --> 00:03:43,456
We pride ourselves on being civilised
here in Warnley.

21
00:03:44,417 --> 00:03:46,955
Dufdon's not much of a place, but...

22
00:03:47,083 --> 00:03:49,791
we're not exactly savages there,
you know, Mr Hoylake.

23
00:03:51,125 --> 00:03:52,366
You think not?

24
00:03:54,292 --> 00:03:56,705
Well, what did you come
to see me about?

25
00:03:57,333 --> 00:03:59,074
Well, I thought perhaps...

26
00:03:59,917 --> 00:04:01,658
You see, I have to get fixed up in digs.

27
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:03,991
You shouldn't have any difficulty.

28
00:04:05,958 --> 00:04:07,244
- Soames.
- 'Yes, sir?'

29
00:04:07,375 --> 00:04:09,537
- You might come in.
- 'Right, Mr Hoylake.'

30
00:04:10,583 --> 00:04:13,121
You'll be working with Soames,
internal audits.

31
00:04:13,833 --> 00:04:15,699
He's got digs somewhere near Top.

32
00:04:15,833 --> 00:04:18,667
Top's the fashionable district.

33
00:04:18,792 --> 00:04:20,328
He's very comfortable, I believe.

34
00:04:20,458 --> 00:04:21,994
Come in.

35
00:04:26,667 --> 00:04:29,956
Charles Soames, Joe Lampton.
Lampton's the new man.

36
00:04:30,083 --> 00:04:31,415
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

37
00:04:31,542 --> 00:04:34,000
He hasn't got anywhere to live.
Can you help him?

38
00:04:34,125 --> 00:04:35,241
Oh, I think so.

39
00:04:36,042 --> 00:04:37,249
I'll leave it to you, then.

40
00:04:38,500 --> 00:04:40,207
We'll have a long session later on.

41
00:04:40,333 --> 00:04:43,201
I'll keep an hour
on Monday morning for you.

42
00:04:44,500 --> 00:04:46,162
This is it.
And that's your desk.

43
00:04:46,292 --> 00:04:48,249
Well, he didn't keep you long
in the firing line.

44
00:04:48,375 --> 00:04:50,367
Joe, this is Miss Samson,
better known as June.

45
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:53,459
Joe Lampton, latest addition
to Treasurer's Department chain gang.

46
00:04:53,583 --> 00:04:55,165
I think I'm going
to enjoy my sentence.

47
00:04:55,292 --> 00:04:57,972
I don't mind you enjoying it,
but you don't have to smack your lips.

48
00:04:58,042 --> 00:05:00,329
Got a hot tip, Charles.
Dog in the second race tonight.

49
00:05:00,458 --> 00:05:02,495
- Interested?
- No! But hold on a minute.

50
00:05:02,625 --> 00:05:04,617
Meet new boy Joe Lampton.
Teddy Merrick.

51
00:05:04,750 --> 00:05:06,366
God help you. I got to run.

52
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:08,020
Well, Charles?
How about those reports?

53
00:05:08,083 --> 00:05:10,996
Oh, aye, Stampton reports.
Now, where did I put them?

54
00:05:11,125 --> 00:05:14,414
Somewhere in here. Have you tried
looking under your skirt?

55
00:05:14,542 --> 00:05:16,659
- What do you mean?
- You're sitting on them, love.

56
00:05:16,792 --> 00:05:19,751
Oh, what a thing
I have to put up with!

57
00:05:19,875 --> 00:05:21,411
Be seeing you.

58
00:05:23,167 --> 00:05:24,499
She belong to us?

59
00:05:24,625 --> 00:05:26,867
Where did you get
that proprietorial plural?

60
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:28,457
I meant the Treasurer's Department.

61
00:05:28,583 --> 00:05:32,623
No, she's Health's typist.
We have our own talent.

62
00:05:34,208 --> 00:05:35,949
Now... digs.

63
00:05:38,542 --> 00:05:40,829
Mabel, would you get me
an outside line?

64
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,492
No, dear, it's not a personal call.

65
00:05:45,208 --> 00:05:46,208
Look, Mabel,

66
00:05:46,333 --> 00:05:48,559
I don't want to argue with you,
just get me an outside line

67
00:05:48,583 --> 00:05:51,303
or I'll put tuppence in your moral
little slot next time I'm passing.

68
00:05:52,042 --> 00:05:55,410
Constipated bitch! You'd think
she had shares in the corporation.

69
00:05:57,583 --> 00:05:59,791
Warnley 4-3-1-5.

70
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,037
That's not for you, lad.

71
00:06:07,167 --> 00:06:09,287
- But I can look, can't I?
- Not like that, you can't.

72
00:06:09,417 --> 00:06:11,750
There's a law against
undressing women in the street.

73
00:06:11,875 --> 00:06:14,743
Hello, is that you, Mrs Thompson?
Charles Soames here.

74
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:17,913
I was wondering if I might bring
a Mr Lampton to see you?

75
00:06:19,208 --> 00:06:22,576
We'll be at the house long before that.
Thank you, Mrs Thompson.

76
00:06:22,708 --> 00:06:25,746
Well, that's as good as fixed,
and at the best digs in Warnley, too.

77
00:06:27,417 --> 00:06:29,249
Is that what you really want?

78
00:06:29,375 --> 00:06:33,415
A clerk's dream?
A girl with a Riviera tan and a Lagonda?

79
00:06:36,875 --> 00:06:38,867
That's what I'm going to have.

80
00:06:41,750 --> 00:06:43,662
Come on, let's go.

81
00:06:43,792 --> 00:06:46,205
Nobody ever goes to Dufdon.

82
00:06:46,333 --> 00:06:48,495
They just pass through it.

83
00:06:48,625 --> 00:06:50,582
A Sunday treat of fish and chips,

84
00:06:50,708 --> 00:06:53,041
wrapped in a greasy
"News of the World".

85
00:06:53,167 --> 00:06:54,533
And for chaps like me,

86
00:06:54,667 --> 00:06:58,115
prospects as appetising
as yesterday's fish-paste sandwich.

87
00:06:58,833 --> 00:07:02,531
You know, when I was a POW,

88
00:07:02,667 --> 00:07:05,330
at least there was a limit
to the time that you serve,

89
00:07:05,458 --> 00:07:08,576
but Dufdon, that seemed
like a lifetime sentence.

90
00:07:08,708 --> 00:07:10,244
You shouldn't be so nostalgic

91
00:07:10,375 --> 00:07:13,334
on your first day away
from the home fires, you know?

92
00:07:13,458 --> 00:07:15,700
I was looking at your river.

93
00:07:15,833 --> 00:07:18,120
Kids fishing and swimming in it.

94
00:07:18,917 --> 00:07:23,287
In Dufdon the canal's like a sewer.

95
00:07:24,750 --> 00:07:28,118
Kids never had a chance
to fish or swim, and the people...

96
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,458
well, I suppose
they never had a chance either.

97
00:07:33,542 --> 00:07:35,499
And somehow here,

98
00:07:35,625 --> 00:07:38,948
well, it's so different.

99
00:07:39,083 --> 00:07:40,540
You wouldn't believe it, Charles.

100
00:07:40,667 --> 00:07:45,412
But you make Warnley sound
so special, Joe, so very special.

101
00:07:45,542 --> 00:07:48,285
It is special. It's not Dufdon.

102
00:07:48,417 --> 00:07:51,125
Not everybody admires
the view from here.

103
00:07:51,250 --> 00:07:55,540
Look, Joe, there's the Top.
That's where the money is.

104
00:07:55,667 --> 00:07:58,205
Lots of lovely houses up there,
you know, Joe.

105
00:07:58,333 --> 00:08:00,541
I'll have one of those.

106
00:08:00,667 --> 00:08:03,159
- I'm going to have the lot.
- Oh, no, you're not!

107
00:08:03,292 --> 00:08:06,285
Not in local government you're not.
Did you ever work it out, brother?

108
00:08:06,417 --> 00:08:08,830
In 20 years' time
you could be sitting in Hoylake's chair.

109
00:08:08,958 --> 00:08:10,290
That's as high as you can go.

110
00:08:10,750 --> 00:08:12,662
And that means Â£1,000 a year,

111
00:08:12,792 --> 00:08:15,580
a semi-detached downtown,
a second-hand Austin

112
00:08:15,708 --> 00:08:17,393
and a wife to match,
if you know what I mean.

113
00:08:17,417 --> 00:08:21,411
I know damn well what you mean.
That's why I'm going to have the lot.

114
00:08:21,542 --> 00:08:23,750
Oh, no.

115
00:08:23,875 --> 00:08:26,709
Oh, by the way, what do you do
for entertainment around here?

116
00:08:26,833 --> 00:08:29,325
Well, there are the flicks, of course.

117
00:08:29,458 --> 00:08:31,825
Teddy Merrick and I play snooker
on Friday nights.

118
00:08:31,958 --> 00:08:33,290
- Do you play?
- Badly.

119
00:08:33,417 --> 00:08:36,376
Oh, and then we have our amateur
dramatic society, the "Thespians".

120
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:38,742
- Are you interested in the theatre?
- Yes.

121
00:08:38,875 --> 00:08:41,743
Look, it's only two weeks away.

122
00:08:42,708 --> 00:08:45,041
And Charlie Soames here,
being a power among the Thespians,

123
00:08:45,167 --> 00:08:47,454
can probably still get
you a ticket for opening night.

124
00:08:47,583 --> 00:08:50,496
- And then he went back to bed?
- Yes.

125
00:08:50,625 --> 00:08:53,618
- To his own bed?
- Val, what's wrong with you?

126
00:08:54,083 --> 00:08:57,872
Did you really think I wouldn't know
the minute I saw you two together?

127
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:59,207
There's nothing to know.

128
00:08:59,333 --> 00:09:02,201
Val, I've no idea
what you're talking about.

129
00:09:02,792 --> 00:09:04,203
You're all upset.

130
00:09:04,333 --> 00:09:06,791
I certainly am upset!
I happen to be...

131
00:09:06,917 --> 00:09:07,917
Who is she?

132
00:09:08,042 --> 00:09:09,908
You should have seen her
in "The Playground".

133
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:12,788
Sex, terrific.

134
00:09:12,917 --> 00:09:14,829
Alice Aisgill. She's French.

135
00:09:15,667 --> 00:09:18,284
That's her husband, lucky devil,
at the end of the front row.

136
00:09:18,417 --> 00:09:22,286
- Val, let's stop this.
- I'll stop it when I get the truth.

137
00:09:24,167 --> 00:09:27,035
Till then I refuse to go to the courtroom.

138
00:09:27,167 --> 00:09:28,703
You can't do that to him.

139
00:09:28,833 --> 00:09:31,120
But she's not married,
she couldn't be.

140
00:09:31,250 --> 00:09:32,912
He means Susan.

141
00:09:33,042 --> 00:09:35,034
- Oh, Susan Brown.
- Yeah.

142
00:09:35,917 --> 00:09:38,204
She's the daughter
of old millionaire Brown.

143
00:09:38,333 --> 00:09:40,620
He owns most of Warnley.

144
00:09:40,750 --> 00:09:42,912
- Have a jujube.
- Thanks.

145
00:09:43,042 --> 00:09:44,874
Joe, don't waste your time.

146
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,959
Susan's out of your reach,
way up in the top drawer.

147
00:09:48,083 --> 00:09:50,416
Speaks as if she had a couple
of hot potatoes in her mouth,

148
00:09:50,542 --> 00:09:53,080
as if her finishing school
hadn't quite finished with her.

149
00:09:55,083 --> 00:09:57,450
Hello, June. Hello Teddy.
Didn't you think she was super?

150
00:09:57,583 --> 00:10:00,326
I don't know who you're talking about,
but I thought she was super.

151
00:10:00,458 --> 00:10:03,041
This is Joe Lampton. Didn't you think
she was absolutely super?

152
00:10:03,167 --> 00:10:06,001
- Oh, absolutely super.
- I thought you were all absolutely super!

153
00:10:06,125 --> 00:10:07,805
Well, children?
What was it like out front?

154
00:10:07,875 --> 00:10:09,875
- Where's June?
- There she is, talking to Bernard,

155
00:10:09,917 --> 00:10:11,203
the foolish virgin.

156
00:10:11,333 --> 00:10:13,013
- What did you think, Joe?
- It wasn't bad.

157
00:10:13,042 --> 00:10:16,535
Oh, damning us with faint praise!
Come and meet some of the company.

158
00:10:16,667 --> 00:10:18,829
I want you to meet Alice Aisgill,
our leading lady.

159
00:10:18,958 --> 00:10:20,915
- Alice, this is Joe Lampton.
- How do you do?

160
00:10:21,042 --> 00:10:22,749
How do you do?
You're new here, aren't you?

161
00:10:22,875 --> 00:10:24,241
I've been here a couple of weeks.

162
00:10:24,375 --> 00:10:26,559
- He's in our department.
- It's Susan Joe wants to meet.

163
00:10:26,583 --> 00:10:28,449
- He's got a thing for Susan.
- Hey, Bernard!

164
00:10:28,583 --> 00:10:30,245
Come and meet Bernard,
our producer.

165
00:10:30,375 --> 00:10:32,287
Bernard, this is Joe Lampton.
Hello, June.

166
00:10:32,417 --> 00:10:33,453
How do you do?

167
00:10:33,583 --> 00:10:35,575
What did you think
of Charles's dawn effect, June?

168
00:10:35,708 --> 00:10:37,199
It came up like thunder.

169
00:10:37,333 --> 00:10:39,199
That's the trouble
with these literal minds.

170
00:10:39,333 --> 00:10:41,825
The playwright's instructions said
"crack of dawn".

171
00:10:41,958 --> 00:10:43,165
That's exactly what we got.

172
00:10:43,292 --> 00:10:45,409
It was a damn good dawn.
You both know it.

173
00:10:45,542 --> 00:10:47,033
Says you!

174
00:10:52,542 --> 00:10:53,874
Come on, Joe.

175
00:10:54,625 --> 00:10:56,912
Hello, Charles. Was I terrible?

176
00:10:57,042 --> 00:11:00,114
You were very good, as a matter of fact.
I want you to meet a friend of mine.

177
00:11:00,250 --> 00:11:02,708
Joe Lampton, Susan Brown.
He liked the show very much.

178
00:11:02,833 --> 00:11:05,075
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

179
00:11:06,083 --> 00:11:08,575
- Where's Jack?
- Oh, he went to fetch his car.

180
00:11:08,708 --> 00:11:10,825
Oh, Charles, you know that scene,
the love scene?

181
00:11:10,958 --> 00:11:13,684
I tried to remember what Bernard said.
Do you think I did it any better?

182
00:11:13,708 --> 00:11:15,244
You were fine.

183
00:11:15,375 --> 00:11:18,495
Jenny, you don't have to take that home.
We might need it again tomorrow night.

184
00:11:18,625 --> 00:11:21,505
- Why don't you just leave it for Tilly?
- You know, if I'd only known...

185
00:11:21,583 --> 00:11:25,327
- If you'd known what?
- If I'd known you'd be so beautiful,

186
00:11:25,875 --> 00:11:28,162
I would have brought you some flowers.

187
00:11:31,542 --> 00:11:33,124
- There you are, Jack.
- Here I am.

188
00:11:33,250 --> 00:11:35,970
You coming for a drink, darling?
We haven't been properly introduced.

189
00:11:36,083 --> 00:11:38,575
I'm Eva, Eva Kent.
And you're Joe, aren't you?

190
00:11:38,708 --> 00:11:40,074
We're going up to the Clarence.

191
00:11:40,208 --> 00:11:42,074
Jack and I have to go home for dinner.

192
00:11:42,208 --> 00:11:43,915
- Oh, what a pity. Cyril!
- Yes?

193
00:11:44,042 --> 00:11:46,204
Joe this is Cyril.
He's my husband, believe it or not.

194
00:11:46,333 --> 00:11:47,414
Cyril, this is Joe.

195
00:11:47,542 --> 00:11:48,623
- Hello.
- Hello again.

196
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:50,742
Teddy was telling me about you,
Teddy Merrick.

197
00:11:50,875 --> 00:11:52,411
I hope you're gonna like it here.

198
00:11:52,542 --> 00:11:54,033
I know I am.

199
00:11:54,833 --> 00:11:59,203
You don't beat about the bush, do you?
I should look out if I were you, Jack.

200
00:11:59,333 --> 00:12:02,371
I think you'll find you have a rival
for Susan's lovely hand.

201
00:12:02,500 --> 00:12:03,616
Joe, this is Jack Wales.

202
00:12:03,750 --> 00:12:05,912
Jack, this is Joe something
from the Treasurer's.

203
00:12:06,042 --> 00:12:07,829
Lampton, Joe Lampton.

204
00:12:07,958 --> 00:12:10,951
You two ought to have a lot in common,
both being intrepid birdmen.

205
00:12:11,083 --> 00:12:12,949
Oh, that. What outfit?

206
00:12:13,083 --> 00:12:15,200
- Wellington's.
- Ah.

207
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:18,326
- Sergeant Observer, eh?
- Yes, how did you know?

208
00:12:18,458 --> 00:12:21,451
Oh, I can tell.
Didn't you ever get beyond Wellington's?

209
00:12:21,583 --> 00:12:25,031
No, I was shot down early,
spent most of the war in a prison camp.

210
00:12:25,167 --> 00:12:28,205
Mm, is that so?
Must have been rough.

211
00:12:29,625 --> 00:12:32,117
- Well, as a matter of fact...
- Come on, Sue.

212
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:34,833
22:40 precisely.
Operation Supper to begin.

213
00:12:34,958 --> 00:12:36,678
What a stink.
I don't know how you stand it.

214
00:12:36,792 --> 00:12:39,032
- Come on, Sue.
- Do come and have a drink with us first.

215
00:12:39,125 --> 00:12:40,605
We'd love to,
but you know Papa Brown.

216
00:12:40,667 --> 00:12:42,507
He likes you there on the dot.
Some other time.

217
00:12:42,583 --> 00:12:44,916
Good night, all.
Good night, Sergeant.

218
00:12:45,042 --> 00:12:47,534
You must tell me about
your POW experiences,

219
00:12:47,667 --> 00:12:49,875
but some other time.

220
00:12:54,125 --> 00:12:56,287
I'll remember the flowers next time.

221
00:12:57,500 --> 00:12:59,867
Good night... sir!

222
00:13:01,417 --> 00:13:03,079
Fricking officer.

223
00:13:03,208 --> 00:13:05,825
Jack Wales was a POW, too.

224
00:13:05,958 --> 00:13:07,574
He escaped.

225
00:13:11,417 --> 00:13:13,704
- Are you nearly ready, darling?
- Mm-hmm.

226
00:14:11,167 --> 00:14:13,454
Hello, Sergeant.

227
00:14:13,583 --> 00:14:15,119
Shopping for lingerie?

228
00:14:15,917 --> 00:14:18,000
What size are you? 44?

229
00:14:18,125 --> 00:14:20,492
Listen, do me a favour, will you?

230
00:14:21,042 --> 00:14:22,283
I know all about you now.

231
00:14:22,417 --> 00:14:25,205
I know you were a squadron leader
with a distinguished war record,

232
00:14:25,333 --> 00:14:28,246
the DSO and all the rest of it,
but just do me a favour:

233
00:14:28,375 --> 00:14:30,583
the war's over,
stop calling me Sergeant!

234
00:14:30,708 --> 00:14:31,915
I'll try to remember.

235
00:14:32,042 --> 00:14:34,250
But, Sergeant,
you're selling me short.

236
00:14:34,375 --> 00:14:36,742
Didn't anyone tell you about my DFC?

237
00:14:42,792 --> 00:14:44,499
He just stood there,
the chinless wonder,

238
00:14:44,625 --> 00:14:46,708
gloating over her
like a bloody watchdog.

239
00:14:46,833 --> 00:14:49,905
All phony accent, putting on
the squadron-leader act with me.

240
00:14:50,042 --> 00:14:51,658
He even threw the DFC at me.

241
00:14:51,792 --> 00:14:55,160
If we'd done whatever it was he did,
we'd have only got the DFM.

242
00:14:55,292 --> 00:14:57,830
- Just medals, no crosses for us.
- Different brands of courage!

243
00:14:57,958 --> 00:15:00,701
Oh, there's Charlie Sales.
I'll see what he's on.

244
00:15:02,750 --> 00:15:05,914
Here, isn't that Susan's father's works?

245
00:15:06,917 --> 00:15:08,499
Joe, you're wasting your time.

246
00:15:08,625 --> 00:15:10,582
These two families,
the Browns and the Waleses,

247
00:15:10,708 --> 00:15:13,701
they've as much brass
as the rest of Warnley rolled together.

248
00:15:13,833 --> 00:15:15,495
Hey, what do you think of that one?

249
00:15:16,375 --> 00:15:18,207
Mm, not bad,

250
00:15:18,333 --> 00:15:19,915
but not grade one.

251
00:15:21,542 --> 00:15:23,158
What do you mean by that?

252
00:15:23,292 --> 00:15:26,080
Time I filled you in
on the Lampton report on love.

253
00:15:26,208 --> 00:15:28,450
I've got a foolproof method
for grading women.

254
00:15:28,583 --> 00:15:33,123
Partly money, partly background,
partly J. Lampton's instinct.

255
00:15:33,250 --> 00:15:35,663
- Now, take Susan Brown.
- Are you offering her to me?

256
00:15:35,792 --> 00:15:38,990
No, seriously, Susan is grade one
on every count.

257
00:15:39,125 --> 00:15:41,726
- You just have to look at her to know.
- Susan's not for you, lad.

258
00:15:41,750 --> 00:15:44,434
- It just so happens that I like her.
- You lust after her, you mean.

259
00:15:44,458 --> 00:15:46,495
No, no, no.
It's not that at all.

260
00:15:46,625 --> 00:15:49,743
Well, it's partly that,
but not just that.

261
00:15:49,875 --> 00:15:53,368
You see, she's so, well...
she's so wholesome.

262
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,116
Do you think
you'd find her as wholesome

263
00:15:55,250 --> 00:15:57,617
if her old man didn't have
a million in the bank?

264
00:15:57,750 --> 00:16:00,037
There are plenty of other
wholesome girls in Warnley.

265
00:16:00,167 --> 00:16:01,749
Like who? Like June?

266
00:16:01,875 --> 00:16:03,366
Yes, like June.

267
00:16:03,500 --> 00:16:05,662
Have you got you some kind
of understanding with her?

268
00:16:05,792 --> 00:16:07,249
Me? Lord, no!

269
00:16:07,375 --> 00:16:09,833
June's a good kid,
but she's got an invalid mother.

270
00:16:09,958 --> 00:16:11,449
And they live off June's salary

271
00:16:11,583 --> 00:16:14,542
so whoever marries June
marries an invalid mother, too.

272
00:16:14,667 --> 00:16:19,241
What you and me should be looking for
is a nice girl with no ties

273
00:16:19,375 --> 00:16:22,288
and a nice family business
in the background, a shop even.

274
00:16:22,417 --> 00:16:26,491
Joe! Two, track two.
We got four to one.

275
00:16:26,625 --> 00:16:28,082
What are you on?

276
00:16:28,208 --> 00:16:32,282
Grade one. I put my two bob
on grade one every time.

277
00:16:32,833 --> 00:16:34,369
Two number two to win, please.

278
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:36,992
How about that baby?

279
00:16:38,625 --> 00:16:41,208
That one? She's grade ten.

280
00:16:41,333 --> 00:16:43,413
Grades nine and over only indulge
on Saturday nights.

281
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:44,980
You want to keep
miles away from them.

282
00:16:45,042 --> 00:16:46,328
Hello. Four to win, please.

283
00:16:46,458 --> 00:16:49,951
Now, grades one like my girl,
they're something really special in bed.

284
00:16:50,083 --> 00:16:51,824
They've almost nothing else to do.

285
00:16:51,958 --> 00:16:54,371
- One to win, please.
- Come on, Joe, there's the bell.

286
00:16:55,208 --> 00:16:57,495
That Brown, he must coin it, you know?

287
00:16:57,625 --> 00:16:59,582
All those chimneys, that's money.

288
00:16:59,708 --> 00:17:02,906
Beautiful, beautiful brass, belching out
every minute of the day and night.

289
00:17:03,042 --> 00:17:05,455
- Come on.
- You know, Charles, I've been thinking.

290
00:17:05,583 --> 00:17:07,666
- About that dramatic club.
- Well?

291
00:17:07,792 --> 00:17:10,660
Remember you said you needed men,
fresh blood and all that?

292
00:17:10,792 --> 00:17:12,454
- Did you mean it?
- I certainly did.

293
00:17:12,583 --> 00:17:14,540
Well, I don't know
if I'll be any good, mind,

294
00:17:14,667 --> 00:17:16,283
- but I'd like to try.
- Oh, I get it.

295
00:17:16,417 --> 00:17:18,329
You're not interested in dramatics,
it's Susan.

296
00:17:18,458 --> 00:17:21,246
Oh, I know.
"You're wasting your time, Joe."

297
00:17:21,375 --> 00:17:23,309
- Do you want to bet on it?
- Did somebody say bet?

298
00:17:23,333 --> 00:17:25,393
I'll bet you never get
the length of a date with her.

299
00:17:25,417 --> 00:17:27,500
- A dollar on it then.
- Right, then. Cut it.

300
00:17:30,667 --> 00:17:32,124
Hello, Susan.

301
00:17:32,833 --> 00:17:33,833
Hello.

302
00:17:33,958 --> 00:17:36,871
You know, I never seem
to get a chance to speak to you.

303
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:39,287
And, well, I only joined the club
because of you

304
00:17:39,417 --> 00:17:42,785
and now, well, I hear
you're not even in the new play.

305
00:17:42,917 --> 00:17:45,330
Somebody else has to have a chance.
It's only fair.

306
00:17:45,458 --> 00:17:48,121
- Gwen is awfully good.
- Quiet, please!

307
00:17:49,500 --> 00:17:50,741
- Damn!
- Quiet, everyone.

308
00:17:50,875 --> 00:17:54,573
- What are you doing after rehearsal?
- We've got a party at home tonight.

309
00:17:54,708 --> 00:17:56,870
Jack's coming to collect me.
He'll be here any minute.

310
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,414
- I thought he was back at Cambridge.
- Oh, he came for the weekend.

311
00:18:00,542 --> 00:18:02,249
Come on, Joe.

312
00:18:02,375 --> 00:18:05,038
Now, er... Same positions.
Come on, Joe, we're wasting time.

313
00:18:05,167 --> 00:18:06,578
Take your coat off.

314
00:18:07,917 --> 00:18:10,079
Come on, Joe, speed it up.
Up to the top of the sofa.

315
00:18:10,208 --> 00:18:13,201
Alice, love, I want to go from the scene
where you defend your lover.

316
00:18:13,333 --> 00:18:15,950
It's the top of page 12.
Now, stand there.

317
00:18:16,083 --> 00:18:18,200
There we are.
"I don't see why..."

318
00:18:18,333 --> 00:18:21,246
Don't forget, love, there's the audience.
Push it right out.

319
00:18:21,375 --> 00:18:23,583
Now, from when I say go.

320
00:18:23,708 --> 00:18:25,199
Ready?

321
00:18:25,333 --> 00:18:26,665
Right!

322
00:18:26,792 --> 00:18:29,000
I don't see why.

323
00:18:29,125 --> 00:18:31,708
He didn't even know my late husband.

324
00:18:31,833 --> 00:18:34,871
I assure you, Inspector,
he has nothing to do with it.

325
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,287
He's something to do
with you, though, hasn't he?

326
00:18:37,417 --> 00:18:40,034
- Really?
- Just what do you mean by that?

327
00:18:40,167 --> 00:18:43,160
I meant you're a friend of hers, sir.
You are, aren't you?

328
00:18:43,917 --> 00:18:46,500
I tell you, I didn't see anything.

329
00:18:46,625 --> 00:18:49,208
It was pitch dark
and the only sign of life

330
00:18:49,333 --> 00:18:52,656
was this old workman
or nightwatchman

331
00:18:52,792 --> 00:18:54,203
sitting by his brassiere.

332
00:19:00,083 --> 00:19:02,200
B-Brazier.

333
00:19:12,625 --> 00:19:16,414
What a wonderful thought.
Erotic vices among the working class.

334
00:19:17,125 --> 00:19:20,573
Let me tell you,
I am working class.

335
00:19:20,708 --> 00:19:22,950
- I didn't mean...
- Working class and proud of it!

336
00:19:23,083 --> 00:19:24,415
You're nothing of the sort!

337
00:19:24,542 --> 00:19:28,661
You're a stockbroker and Alice's lover
and suspected of murder in the play.

338
00:19:28,792 --> 00:19:31,705
Now, shut up, the lot of you.
We'll start again.

339
00:19:31,833 --> 00:19:33,790
When you come to say,
"What's the point?"

340
00:19:33,917 --> 00:19:37,285
I want you to make a turn,
a half-turn towards the window.

341
00:19:52,917 --> 00:19:56,786
Yes, it was funny.

342
00:19:56,917 --> 00:20:00,285
- I didn't mean to snap at you.
- Oh, forget it.

343
00:20:01,708 --> 00:20:05,952
- Will you have a coffee with me?
- No, but you may buy me a drink.

344
00:20:08,333 --> 00:20:11,201
- Can you drive?
- Yes, oddly enough.

345
00:20:12,250 --> 00:20:15,448
Of course, I never owned a car,
but I learned to drive in the RAF.

346
00:20:16,208 --> 00:20:17,289
Here.

347
00:20:18,708 --> 00:20:20,665
You're very touchy, aren't you?

348
00:20:25,750 --> 00:20:29,494
- Where to?
- To the St Clair. It's quiet.

349
00:20:43,458 --> 00:20:45,450
That's the Browns' place.

350
00:20:45,583 --> 00:20:48,291
Yes, I know. I walked past it.

351
00:20:49,500 --> 00:20:52,208
Hmm, they seem
to have something on tonight.

352
00:20:52,333 --> 00:20:54,666
Susan told me
they were having a party.

353
00:21:00,167 --> 00:21:03,035
What a place! It's like a castle.

354
00:21:04,042 --> 00:21:06,659
Charles tells me
they've even got a swimming pool.

355
00:21:08,125 --> 00:21:10,242
They've got just about everything,
haven't they?

356
00:21:11,417 --> 00:21:13,249
I wouldn't say that.

357
00:21:17,833 --> 00:21:21,952
I thought you were coming
the lady of the mansion over me.

358
00:21:22,083 --> 00:21:25,656
My father didn't own
an engineering works or a mill.

359
00:21:25,792 --> 00:21:28,125
He never even owned his own house.

360
00:21:28,250 --> 00:21:31,869
But that doesn't mean I can't drive a car
or pronounce bra... brazier.

361
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,117
But who cares about these things?

362
00:21:34,250 --> 00:21:36,082
Some people do.

363
00:21:36,708 --> 00:21:38,540
It's Susan, isn't it?

364
00:21:38,667 --> 00:21:40,704
That's what's bothering you.

365
00:21:40,833 --> 00:21:42,870
It's Jack Wales really.

366
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:45,413
That type, they make me mad.

367
00:21:45,542 --> 00:21:48,785
The boys with the big mouths
and the silver spoon stuck in them.

368
00:21:48,917 --> 00:21:53,161
They think they can take everything
worth having by a sort of divine right.

369
00:21:53,917 --> 00:21:56,125
Calling me Sergeant!

370
00:21:56,250 --> 00:21:57,661
It is Susan.

371
00:21:57,792 --> 00:22:00,250
- Alf, can we have the same again?
- Right, Mrs Aisgill.

372
00:22:00,375 --> 00:22:01,375
You're jealous.

373
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:04,957
I suppose I am.

374
00:22:06,042 --> 00:22:09,365
Well, why don't you phone the girl
and ask her to go out with you, then?

375
00:22:10,583 --> 00:22:11,915
Why don't you?

376
00:22:13,417 --> 00:22:17,366
You feel inferior to Jack Wales?

377
00:22:19,500 --> 00:22:21,241
No, I don't.

378
00:22:22,583 --> 00:22:26,623
I've a feeling, and I know I'm right.
I know she doesn't want him.

379
00:22:27,875 --> 00:22:29,992
I suppose you think I'm conceited.

380
00:22:31,833 --> 00:22:34,826
Young and terribly inexperienced.

381
00:22:35,625 --> 00:22:37,116
But not conceited.

382
00:22:38,625 --> 00:22:41,914
Well, if that's the way
you really feel about her,

383
00:22:42,042 --> 00:22:43,954
then you must be right.

384
00:22:45,083 --> 00:22:48,576
Your trouble is
you don't believe enough in yourself.

385
00:22:50,125 --> 00:22:52,162
I'll tell you something, Alice.

386
00:22:54,792 --> 00:22:56,078
I like you.

387
00:22:57,000 --> 00:22:59,663
I don't mean sex, I mean "like" you.

388
00:23:00,708 --> 00:23:02,040
I like to talk to you.

389
00:23:03,500 --> 00:23:05,457
I just like you.

390
00:23:08,292 --> 00:23:12,286
You look about 18 sometimes.
Do you know that?

391
00:23:15,250 --> 00:23:19,369
You remind me of a boy I used to know
at the university in Paris.

392
00:23:21,708 --> 00:23:24,667
It must be funny being French
here in Warnley.

393
00:23:28,667 --> 00:23:29,748
No.

394
00:23:30,833 --> 00:23:32,870
It's not funny.

395
00:23:34,083 --> 00:23:35,745
Are you very unhappy, Alice?

396
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:39,207
Not very.

397
00:23:40,458 --> 00:23:42,120
Come on.

398
00:23:54,292 --> 00:23:57,831
- Susan, there's a telephone call for you.
- Oh, damn. Who is it?

399
00:23:57,958 --> 00:24:00,996
It's a gentleman.
I think he said Mr Lampton.

400
00:24:01,958 --> 00:24:03,039
What will I tell him?

401
00:24:03,167 --> 00:24:06,126
- Oh, it's all right, Mary. I'll take it.
- Very well, Miss Susan.

402
00:24:07,708 --> 00:24:09,916
Hello? Susan Brown.

403
00:24:11,500 --> 00:24:13,787
Oh, hello, Joe.
I didn't know it was you.

404
00:24:15,125 --> 00:24:17,412
Saturday evening?
I'd love to, but...

405
00:24:18,125 --> 00:24:19,661
Hold on a minute.

406
00:24:26,208 --> 00:24:28,996
Hello, Joe?
I've just looked up in my book

407
00:24:29,125 --> 00:24:32,368
and I've got another engagement
on Saturday.

408
00:24:32,500 --> 00:24:34,583
Yes, I'd love to some other time.

409
00:24:35,333 --> 00:24:37,791
Gosh, here's Mummy. Bye!

410
00:24:37,917 --> 00:24:40,785
- Who was that telephoning, Susan?
- Joe Lampton.

411
00:24:40,917 --> 00:24:43,000
- I met him at the Thespians.
- What did he want?

412
00:24:43,125 --> 00:24:45,037
He wanted to take me
to the cinema on Saturday.

413
00:24:45,167 --> 00:24:47,750
But we don't know him, do we?
Socially, I mean.

414
00:24:47,875 --> 00:24:50,333
Oh, I don't suppose so.
He works at the town hall.

415
00:24:50,458 --> 00:24:51,458
Really!

416
00:24:51,583 --> 00:24:54,291
Oh, it's all right, Mummy,
I told him I had a previous appointment.

417
00:24:54,417 --> 00:24:57,205
But only because I had.
He's very nice really.

418
00:24:57,333 --> 00:25:01,247
- What did you say his name was?
- Lampton, Joe Lampton.

419
00:25:01,375 --> 00:25:03,617
Curious names
some of these people have.

420
00:25:04,417 --> 00:25:06,579
Listen, Alice, tell me,

421
00:25:06,708 --> 00:25:10,247
well, supposing you were a girl,
I mean a young girl,

422
00:25:10,375 --> 00:25:13,243
and I asked you out,
I mean, would you hang up in a hurry

423
00:25:13,375 --> 00:25:15,207
just because your mother
came into the room?

424
00:25:15,333 --> 00:25:17,620
Look, Joe,
if I had a mother like Mrs Brown,

425
00:25:17,750 --> 00:25:20,333
I would hang up in a great hurry
whenever she came into the room.

426
00:25:20,458 --> 00:25:22,165
Aren't you two coming?
Where's Charles?

427
00:25:22,292 --> 00:25:24,033
He'll be over in a minute.

428
00:25:24,167 --> 00:25:26,830
I still think she was trying
to give me the brush-off.

429
00:25:26,958 --> 00:25:30,998
Well, supposing she was?
Keep trying, call her again.

430
00:25:31,125 --> 00:25:33,583
- Do you really mean it?
- Of course.

431
00:25:33,708 --> 00:25:34,744
Why not?

432
00:25:35,708 --> 00:25:38,906
Oh, while I'm handing out advice,

433
00:25:40,042 --> 00:25:42,079
do you mind if I tell you
about our last scene,

434
00:25:42,208 --> 00:25:43,540
the bedroom one?

435
00:25:44,375 --> 00:25:46,458
Oh, I know, I...
I made a muck of it.

436
00:25:47,708 --> 00:25:49,574
You're not frightened of me, are you?

437
00:25:50,958 --> 00:25:51,958
No.

438
00:25:53,083 --> 00:25:55,791
Well, you must take hold of me
as if you meant it.

439
00:25:55,917 --> 00:25:58,079
I'm not fragile, you know?
I won't break.

440
00:25:58,583 --> 00:25:59,583
I'll try, Alice.

441
00:26:01,958 --> 00:26:03,824
Is it so difficult?

442
00:26:07,292 --> 00:26:10,706
Another bitter, a gin and tonic
and two gins and lime.

443
00:26:10,833 --> 00:26:12,825
- Have you got any crisps?
- I think so, sir.

444
00:26:14,250 --> 00:26:16,708
Hello, Alice.
I was just telling them about Gwen.

445
00:26:16,833 --> 00:26:19,473
Bernard and I were talking to her
after the rehearsal the other day

446
00:26:19,583 --> 00:26:23,532
and she said, "I'd take him on myself,
but I can't bear bandy-legged men."

447
00:26:26,958 --> 00:26:29,245
Good evening.
Bernard said you'd be here.

448
00:26:29,792 --> 00:26:32,034
Hello, George.
This is a surprise.

449
00:26:32,167 --> 00:26:33,749
It's not a social call.

450
00:26:35,708 --> 00:26:37,574
- I think you know everybody.
- I think so.

451
00:26:37,708 --> 00:26:40,542
And of course this is Joe Lampton,
my lover in the play.

452
00:26:40,667 --> 00:26:42,579
The war hero.

453
00:26:42,708 --> 00:26:45,542
Well, I'm always glad
to meet one of Alice's lovers.

454
00:26:45,667 --> 00:26:48,535
Let me have the keys, will you?
I've got to take the CitroÃ«n.

455
00:26:48,667 --> 00:26:50,579
- Why?
- My ignition's gone

456
00:26:50,708 --> 00:26:52,995
and I've got to get
over to Leeds tonight.

457
00:26:53,125 --> 00:26:54,366
So late?

458
00:26:54,500 --> 00:26:56,787
Something cropped up unexpectedly.

459
00:26:56,917 --> 00:26:58,499
I'll be away a couple of days.

460
00:27:03,958 --> 00:27:05,574
But, er...

461
00:27:05,708 --> 00:27:08,041
What about the car for tomorrow?

462
00:27:08,625 --> 00:27:09,625
What about it?

463
00:27:09,750 --> 00:27:13,289
You know I was going to take Elspeth
to Manchester to the ballet.

464
00:27:13,417 --> 00:27:15,704
You know I arranged it weeks ago.

465
00:27:16,875 --> 00:27:20,448
Well, you'll just have to make it
some other time, won't you?

466
00:27:20,583 --> 00:27:22,700
Enjoy yourselves, everybody.

467
00:27:23,542 --> 00:27:25,249
Good night, dear.

468
00:27:34,542 --> 00:27:37,285
I thought you said you were going
to be word-perfect tonight.

469
00:27:37,417 --> 00:27:39,457
- I thought I were till I got on stage.
- Bernard...

470
00:27:45,250 --> 00:27:47,207
You know what that means?

471
00:27:47,333 --> 00:27:49,620
A couple of days'
hard labour with his secretary.

472
00:27:49,750 --> 00:27:52,242
Yeah. Darn shame.

473
00:28:04,833 --> 00:28:06,369
Shall I see you home?

474
00:28:07,708 --> 00:28:08,789
No.

475
00:28:09,667 --> 00:28:12,125
Alice, I hate to see you hurt.

476
00:28:12,250 --> 00:28:13,832
I'm not hurt.

477
00:28:13,958 --> 00:28:16,450
You sure you don't want me
to take you home?

478
00:28:17,583 --> 00:28:19,074
I'd like to.

479
00:28:19,958 --> 00:28:21,449
I'd rather not.

480
00:28:25,708 --> 00:28:27,324
Good night, Joe.

481
00:29:00,833 --> 00:29:02,620
- Joe!
- Shh!

482
00:29:02,750 --> 00:29:05,208
What are you doing here?
I was just thinking about you.

483
00:29:05,333 --> 00:29:06,665
You were?

484
00:29:06,792 --> 00:29:09,284
I was thinking about you
when I passed the town hall

485
00:29:09,417 --> 00:29:11,033
and the thought stuck on.

486
00:29:11,167 --> 00:29:14,740
Like a hangover?
What were you thinking about me?

487
00:29:14,875 --> 00:29:17,709
Nothing exactly.
What are you doing here?

488
00:29:17,833 --> 00:29:21,372
Oh, I often come down here
to do the library accounts.

489
00:29:22,708 --> 00:29:23,994
You know, Susan...

490
00:29:26,208 --> 00:29:28,120
...you're looking very pretty.

491
00:29:29,250 --> 00:29:31,037
Thank you kindly, sir.

492
00:29:31,167 --> 00:29:32,658
Do you think this is any good?

493
00:29:32,792 --> 00:29:34,792
I wanted the new Bates,
but there's a waiting list.

494
00:29:34,875 --> 00:29:38,368
If you could wait for about ten minutes,
we can go and have coffee together.

495
00:29:38,500 --> 00:29:40,742
I can't, I'm meeting my mother for lunch.

496
00:29:40,875 --> 00:29:44,448
Oh, well... they tell me
there's a very good film on at the Regal.

497
00:29:44,583 --> 00:29:46,119
The musical? Super!

498
00:29:46,250 --> 00:29:47,250
- Have you seen it?
- No.

499
00:29:47,375 --> 00:29:48,476
- Would you like to go?
- Yes.

500
00:29:48,500 --> 00:29:49,832
When?

501
00:29:50,750 --> 00:29:52,742
- Oh.
- You know, Susan...

502
00:29:56,250 --> 00:29:59,618
...you're not only pretty,
you're beautiful.

503
00:30:02,833 --> 00:30:03,869
Tonight, then.

504
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:06,583
Oh, tonight will do
like no other night has ever done.

505
00:30:07,625 --> 00:30:10,083
I'll pick you up at your house,
at seven o'clock.

506
00:30:10,208 --> 00:30:12,791
No, I'd rather meet you there.

507
00:30:12,917 --> 00:30:15,159
Seven o'clock at the Regal.

508
00:30:19,500 --> 00:30:22,413
Seven o'clock, then, at the Regal.

509
00:30:25,708 --> 00:30:27,199
- Charles!
- Yeah?

510
00:30:27,333 --> 00:30:29,040
- Charles, lend me a quid.
- What for?

511
00:30:29,167 --> 00:30:31,284
- Come on, I'm late. I'll explain later.
- All right.

512
00:30:31,417 --> 00:30:33,033
Hurry up, man! Thank you.

513
00:30:33,167 --> 00:30:35,910
By the way, do you remember
that bet I made you the other day?

514
00:30:36,042 --> 00:30:37,954
- Which one?
- At the dog track, remember?

515
00:30:38,083 --> 00:30:40,826
Well, you've lost,
so I only owe you 15 bob.

516
00:30:40,958 --> 00:30:42,950
- No!
- Yes!

517
00:30:45,333 --> 00:30:48,781
You know, you're the sort of girl
I like to take out.

518
00:30:48,917 --> 00:30:50,658
- Why?
- Well...

519
00:30:50,792 --> 00:30:53,626
there's your shape
and your size and...

520
00:30:53,750 --> 00:30:56,083
the sheen in your hair,

521
00:30:56,208 --> 00:30:58,450
a sort of light in your eyes.

522
00:30:58,583 --> 00:31:02,281
Oh, but... most important
because I think you're a dear kipper.

523
00:31:02,417 --> 00:31:05,125
- A what?
- A dear kipper.

524
00:31:05,250 --> 00:31:06,832
What a lovely word!
What does it mean?

525
00:31:06,958 --> 00:31:09,416
My mother called me that
every time I asked her for something

526
00:31:09,542 --> 00:31:12,205
that cost more than she could afford.

527
00:31:12,333 --> 00:31:14,746
I'd like to meet your mother.
She sounds fun.

528
00:31:14,875 --> 00:31:16,741
She's dead.

529
00:31:19,167 --> 00:31:20,703
I'm sorry.

530
00:31:20,833 --> 00:31:23,701
My mother and my father
were both killed in an air raid.

531
00:31:25,083 --> 00:31:27,541
I don't even know
if it was an air raid.

532
00:31:27,667 --> 00:31:30,626
The only bombs ever
to have dropped on Dufdon.

533
00:31:30,750 --> 00:31:32,742
Probably by mistake.

534
00:31:34,167 --> 00:31:37,001
Anyhow, they...
they had to fall on our house.

535
00:31:37,125 --> 00:31:39,617
Joe, how awful for you!

536
00:31:39,750 --> 00:31:41,662
I'm terribly sorry.

537
00:31:43,083 --> 00:31:45,075
It's all right.

538
00:31:45,208 --> 00:31:48,076
It happened a long time ago.

539
00:31:48,208 --> 00:31:51,531
- Evening! Aren't you gonna offer me a drink?
- Jack!

540
00:31:51,667 --> 00:31:54,705
I thought you were washing
your hair tonight. Waiter!

541
00:31:54,833 --> 00:31:56,040
You're not a hairdresser, too?

542
00:31:56,167 --> 00:31:58,454
No, I'm not a hairdresser
and I'm not your bloody batman.

543
00:31:58,583 --> 00:31:59,915
A large Scotch for me, please.

544
00:32:00,042 --> 00:32:02,204
- Don't let us keep you.
- Not at all, it's a pleasure.

545
00:32:02,333 --> 00:32:05,213
As a matter of fact, I've wanted
to have a chat with you for a long time,

546
00:32:05,333 --> 00:32:06,869
about your acting actually.

547
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:09,993
I think you have
distinct comic possibilities.

548
00:32:10,125 --> 00:32:11,661
Don't you agree, Susan?

549
00:32:13,125 --> 00:32:14,661
If you'll excuse me...

550
00:32:17,708 --> 00:32:21,031
If I live to be 100, Jack,
I'll never forgive you for this.

551
00:32:21,167 --> 00:32:23,910
I thought you were going
to wash your hair tonight.

552
00:32:26,250 --> 00:32:28,367
Well, I don't know
who you think you're dealing with,

553
00:32:28,500 --> 00:32:30,492
but you can take that away for a start.

554
00:32:30,625 --> 00:32:33,288
I want to build an administration block,
not a ladies' lavatory.

555
00:32:33,417 --> 00:32:37,206
We make machine tools at Brown's,
remember? Not silk stockings.

556
00:32:37,333 --> 00:32:39,791
You should never have let
this young man get so far with it.

557
00:32:39,917 --> 00:32:43,115
I only saw a sketch, Mr Brown.
It looked very handsome.

558
00:32:43,250 --> 00:32:45,833
You come back tomorrow
with some designs that I can use

559
00:32:45,958 --> 00:32:48,416
or don't bother to come back at all,
either of you.

560
00:32:48,542 --> 00:32:49,749
Go on, get out!

561
00:32:49,875 --> 00:32:52,333
Miss Fisher!
What's happened to that London call?

562
00:32:52,458 --> 00:32:54,745
- 'It's engaged, sir.'
- Will you try the other number?

563
00:32:54,875 --> 00:32:57,788
- I must get those shares on the market.
- 'Very good, sir.'

564
00:32:59,250 --> 00:33:02,948
- Hello. What are you two doing here?
- Susan's just told me she's going out.

565
00:33:03,083 --> 00:33:05,826
- I want you to tell her not to.
- Oh, why?

566
00:33:05,958 --> 00:33:08,291
For one thing, we have guests
and it will upset my table.

567
00:33:08,417 --> 00:33:11,330
For another,
it's that Joe Lampton again.

568
00:33:11,458 --> 00:33:14,166
Can't you put him off for once, Susan,
just to please your mother?

569
00:33:14,292 --> 00:33:15,828
No, I can't.

570
00:33:15,958 --> 00:33:17,199
It isn't just tonight.

571
00:33:17,333 --> 00:33:20,371
Mother doesn't like him.
She doesn't think he's suitable.

572
00:33:21,208 --> 00:33:22,208
Do you?

573
00:33:22,333 --> 00:33:24,620
I don't know about suitable,
but I like him.

574
00:33:24,750 --> 00:33:26,582
He calls me "a dear kipper".

575
00:33:27,583 --> 00:33:28,790
A what?

576
00:33:28,917 --> 00:33:31,409
You explain to Mother, Daddy.
I'm sure you know.

577
00:33:31,917 --> 00:33:35,035
Goodbye, I'm late, and don't be cross.
You know I love you both.

578
00:33:35,167 --> 00:33:38,205
That doesn't get me anywhere
with my dinner party.

579
00:33:40,250 --> 00:33:41,832
Why didn't you stop her?

580
00:33:41,958 --> 00:33:44,878
Stopping her from seeing this young man
isn't the way to put an end to it.

581
00:33:44,958 --> 00:33:46,540
Then what is?

582
00:33:46,667 --> 00:33:49,956
Or don't you mind her getting mixed up
with a small-town nobody?

583
00:33:50,083 --> 00:33:52,996
Small-town nobodies
sometimes do well enough.

584
00:33:53,125 --> 00:33:55,833
You saw nought wrong
with one once, Mother.

585
00:33:55,958 --> 00:33:58,416
I happen to be Susan's mother,
not yours.

586
00:33:58,542 --> 00:33:59,999
Now, listen,

587
00:34:00,125 --> 00:34:03,368
will you stop bothering your head
about Joe Lampton

588
00:34:03,500 --> 00:34:04,616
and just leave it to me?

589
00:34:06,750 --> 00:34:08,036
Get me the town hall.

590
00:34:08,167 --> 00:34:11,007
I have a minute or two.
I thought we might have a little chat.

591
00:34:11,333 --> 00:34:13,700
You've picked up the work very quickly.

592
00:34:13,833 --> 00:34:16,905
- Six months now, isn't it?
- Not quite.

593
00:34:17,042 --> 00:34:20,456
You're a bright lad, Lampton,
and you've also a lot of sense.

594
00:34:22,917 --> 00:34:26,115
Sense enough, I'm sure, not to resent
what I'm going to say to you.

595
00:34:27,208 --> 00:34:30,827
This is a small town, Lampton.
I've lived in it all my life.

596
00:34:30,958 --> 00:34:32,915
I know the people,
I know their business.

597
00:34:33,042 --> 00:34:36,831
Councillor Brown, for instance,
I went to school with him.

598
00:34:37,542 --> 00:34:40,410
You know, of course, he's chairman
of the establishment committee.

599
00:34:40,542 --> 00:34:44,786
- Yes, but I don't quite see...
- He's a powerful man, Lampton.

600
00:34:45,833 --> 00:34:49,156
That engineering works of his,
built it up from nothing.

601
00:34:49,292 --> 00:34:51,750
Now it's the biggest
of its kind in Warnley.

602
00:34:51,875 --> 00:34:53,082
Ruthless!

603
00:34:53,208 --> 00:34:55,746
Well, I suppose you've got
to be ruthless in business.

604
00:34:55,875 --> 00:34:57,537
He knows what he wants
and he gets it.

605
00:34:57,667 --> 00:34:59,750
He can drive a coach-and-four
through that committee

606
00:34:59,875 --> 00:35:01,457
anytime he wants.

607
00:35:02,625 --> 00:35:04,787
Every council's the same.

608
00:35:04,917 --> 00:35:07,876
There's always one strong man,

609
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:12,574
a danger man
as far as the officials are concerned.

610
00:35:12,708 --> 00:35:15,826
Mind you, no matter how influential
any councillor may be,

611
00:35:15,958 --> 00:35:19,781
he can't touch our jobs,
he can't downgrade us.

612
00:35:19,917 --> 00:35:24,036
But when it comes to promotion,
there's the rub.

613
00:35:24,167 --> 00:35:26,454
That's a different matter.

614
00:35:26,583 --> 00:35:29,121
- You follow me, Joe?
- I follow you.

615
00:35:29,250 --> 00:35:30,832
I thought you would.

616
00:35:31,875 --> 00:35:34,743
Do you mind if I give you
a word of advice, Joe?

617
00:35:34,875 --> 00:35:36,662
It's this.

618
00:35:36,792 --> 00:35:41,241
- Find a girl, a girl of your own...
- Class? Is that what you mean?

619
00:35:41,375 --> 00:35:42,741
A girl of my own class?

620
00:35:42,875 --> 00:35:45,413
Well, let's say background.

621
00:35:45,542 --> 00:35:48,580
Plenty of nice girls in Warnley,
pretty ones, too.

622
00:35:50,375 --> 00:35:55,291
You find the right kind of girl, Joe,
you'll go a long way here in Warnley.

623
00:35:58,042 --> 00:36:00,580
You wouldn't believe it!
Who the hell he thinks he is,

624
00:36:00,708 --> 00:36:03,166
sitting there like Al Capone
putting the finger on me!

625
00:36:03,292 --> 00:36:06,660
Oh, I got the works, the chairman
of the establishment committee.

626
00:36:06,792 --> 00:36:09,626
As neat a job of blackmail
as you ever saw.

627
00:36:09,750 --> 00:36:12,584
"You follow me, Joe?"
Yes, he even called me Joe.

628
00:36:12,708 --> 00:36:15,108
"If you don't leave Susan alone,
there will be no promotion."

629
00:36:15,208 --> 00:36:17,368
I told you months ago,
I warned you, she's not for you!

630
00:36:17,417 --> 00:36:19,830
Another couple of minutes,
I would have taken his promotion

631
00:36:19,958 --> 00:36:22,166
and shoved it up his... waistcoat.

632
00:36:22,292 --> 00:36:25,706
- Fares, please.
- Two to Warnley Theatre, please.

633
00:36:35,958 --> 00:36:37,824
What's the matter?

634
00:36:37,958 --> 00:36:39,699
Nothing.

635
00:36:41,333 --> 00:36:43,040
Just mood.

636
00:36:44,708 --> 00:36:46,791
I have bad moods sometimes.

637
00:36:47,708 --> 00:36:50,701
- Don't you?
- Damnable moods.

638
00:36:50,833 --> 00:36:52,916
Take today for instance.

639
00:36:57,708 --> 00:36:58,915
Here.

640
00:37:04,375 --> 00:37:05,911
You need a drink.

641
00:37:06,875 --> 00:37:08,082
No.

642
00:37:09,042 --> 00:37:11,250
You want me to drive you home?

643
00:37:12,417 --> 00:37:14,158
No.

644
00:37:14,292 --> 00:37:17,956
- I'd like to go to Sparrow Hill.
- It's cold up there.

645
00:37:18,083 --> 00:37:19,870
That's what I want.

646
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:22,583
Somewhere cold and clean.

647
00:37:22,708 --> 00:37:26,156
With no people, no dirty people.

648
00:37:42,458 --> 00:37:44,575
- Something going on there?
- Well, you know Alice.

649
00:37:44,708 --> 00:37:45,744
Don't be catty, darling.

650
00:37:45,875 --> 00:37:48,117
Alice is a very charming
and very long-suffering person.

651
00:37:48,250 --> 00:37:50,242
Alice is all woman.

652
00:37:51,875 --> 00:37:53,491
George is away for the weekend.

653
00:37:53,625 --> 00:37:55,992
He is often away for weekends.

654
00:37:59,625 --> 00:38:02,493
- How did you meet him?
- I was a teacher,

655
00:38:02,625 --> 00:38:04,833
what you call an exchange teacher.

656
00:38:04,958 --> 00:38:09,077
I came over for one year in '37
and I met George.

657
00:38:13,708 --> 00:38:16,041
Can't imagine you as a teacher.

658
00:38:18,292 --> 00:38:20,204
I was a good teacher.

659
00:39:21,500 --> 00:39:23,162
Oh, Alice!

660
00:39:24,083 --> 00:39:25,915
Don't say anything.

661
00:39:31,333 --> 00:39:34,701
This is a very moral kind of a girl.

662
00:40:06,708 --> 00:40:07,915
Morning, Charles.

663
00:40:08,042 --> 00:40:10,455
I don't understand this.
I hardly know the man.

664
00:40:13,667 --> 00:40:18,332
Hmm, seems a good job,
and in Dufdon.

665
00:40:18,458 --> 00:40:22,077
- What are you gonna do about it?
- I don't know. See him, I suppose.

666
00:40:22,208 --> 00:40:25,246
Chances are, my days at the Treasurer's
Department are numbered anyway.

667
00:40:25,375 --> 00:40:27,412
Oh, don't be daft!

668
00:40:28,458 --> 00:40:30,791
Why don't you look at it
as a free trip home.

669
00:40:30,917 --> 00:40:33,000
Home? My home's a bombsite.

670
00:40:51,500 --> 00:40:53,082
This is my house.

671
00:40:54,667 --> 00:40:56,203
It's my house.

672
00:41:02,625 --> 00:41:04,491
It used to be mine, too.

673
00:41:05,375 --> 00:41:07,037
I lived here once upon a time.

674
00:41:07,625 --> 00:41:09,787
A bomb fell from the sky.

675
00:41:09,917 --> 00:41:11,579
I know.

676
00:41:11,708 --> 00:41:13,370
Do you want to see my garden?

677
00:41:13,958 --> 00:41:15,039
Aye.

678
00:41:22,958 --> 00:41:24,039
Look!

679
00:41:30,792 --> 00:41:33,535
Oh, they're pretty.
What are they called?

680
00:41:33,667 --> 00:41:35,829
Flowers. They're called flowers.

681
00:41:38,958 --> 00:41:41,951
Ethel? Ethel, come here at once.

682
00:41:42,083 --> 00:41:43,665
My mother.

683
00:41:43,792 --> 00:41:45,328
At once, Ethel.

684
00:41:45,458 --> 00:41:47,245
Come here at once.

685
00:41:48,542 --> 00:41:51,000
If I've told you once,
I've told you a dozen times.

686
00:41:51,125 --> 00:41:52,582
- You must be new here.
- No.

687
00:41:52,708 --> 00:41:54,791
But you weren't here
in the old days.

688
00:41:54,917 --> 00:41:57,625
- I was just looking at the house.
- Go on, into the house!

689
00:41:57,750 --> 00:42:00,458
I just don't like her
talking to strangers, that's all.

690
00:42:00,583 --> 00:42:02,199
But I'm not really a stranger.

691
00:42:02,333 --> 00:42:04,746
- Vera!
- All right, all right.

692
00:42:48,125 --> 00:42:50,742
- Uncle Nat.
- Is that you, Joe?

693
00:42:50,875 --> 00:42:52,036
Yes, Auntie.

694
00:42:52,167 --> 00:42:55,535
Come and tell us all about it.
Did you see Mr Darnley? Was he nice?

695
00:42:55,667 --> 00:42:57,704
I haven't seen him yet.
My appointment's for four.

696
00:42:57,833 --> 00:43:01,247
Oh, well, that's fine.
I've just made tea.

697
00:43:01,375 --> 00:43:04,868
It's nice to have you back,
just like old times.

698
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:07,287
Nat can move in with Ruben.

699
00:43:07,417 --> 00:43:10,410
Then you can have
your own room back.

700
00:43:10,542 --> 00:43:12,158
Window's all right.

701
00:43:12,292 --> 00:43:15,911
Your cousin finally stirred himself
and mended that broken pane.

702
00:43:16,958 --> 00:43:19,621
Here, we've...
we've missed you, lad.

703
00:43:22,375 --> 00:43:26,164
It's right grand
to have you back home again.

704
00:43:30,292 --> 00:43:32,909
I'm not sure if I'm going
to take that job, Auntie.

705
00:43:34,375 --> 00:43:35,707
Why ever not?

706
00:43:36,875 --> 00:43:38,366
Well...

707
00:43:38,500 --> 00:43:42,744
- It isn't that I wasn't happy here.
- I know that.

708
00:43:42,875 --> 00:43:44,161
Good and thick.

709
00:43:44,292 --> 00:43:46,955
Aye, so that the spoon stands up in it.

710
00:43:48,542 --> 00:43:50,579
Well, it's just that...

711
00:43:51,583 --> 00:43:54,246
Warnley's a different kind of a town.

712
00:43:54,375 --> 00:43:56,492
There's a different sort of people.

713
00:43:56,625 --> 00:43:58,457
Got a girl, Joe?

714
00:43:58,583 --> 00:44:01,291
- Aye, I have.
- Go on.

715
00:44:01,417 --> 00:44:03,875
Hear that, Nat?

716
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:06,617
Her name's Susan, Susan Brown.

717
00:44:06,750 --> 00:44:09,163
Go on, you great lummocks!

